# Type Design Rules

## Event Types

Event types should be immutable. Prefer `readonly struct`; a `class` is allowed only when the event needs polymorphism or carries a reference type that would box inside a struct. All current events in this project are simple, non-polymorphic data and must be `readonly struct` **implementing `IEvent`** (`Core/Events/IEvent.cs`) so `IEventBus` generic methods are type-safe.

| Event | Folder |
|---|---|
| (bus only: `IEvent`, `IEventBus`, `EventBus`) | `Core/Events/` |
| `HealthChangedEvent`, `HealEvent`, `DamageEvent`, `EntityDiedEvent` | `Gameplay/Combat/Events/` (`Gameplay.Combat.Events` namespace) |
| `BuffAppliedEvent`, `BuffRemovedEvent` | `Ability/Buff/Events/` (when implemented) |
| `StatChangedEvent` | `Gameplay/Stats/Events/` |
| `CooldownStartedEvent`, `CooldownEndedEvent` | `Ability/Events/` |

Do not define gameplay event structs in `Core/`. Place each event per `architecture.mdc`, Event Placement. Death event name is **`EntityDiedEvent`** (not `EnemyDiedEvent`).

```csharp
// Correct — Gameplay/Combat/Events/DamageEvent.cs
public readonly struct DamageEvent : IEvent
{
    public ICombatEntity Source { get; }
    public ICombatEntity Target { get; }
    public DamageType DamageType { get; }
    public float Amount { get; }
    public bool IsCrit { get; }

    public DamageEvent(ICombatEntity source, ICombatEntity target, DamageType damageType, float amount, bool isCrit) { ... }
}

// Wrong — do not silently use class for a simple data event
public class DamageEvent { ... }
```

## Context Types

`DamageContext` is a `readonly struct`, not a class. It holds `ICombatEntity` references, but storing a reference type (an interface implemented by a `MonoBehaviour`) in a struct field does not box — boxing only happens when a *value type* is converted to a reference/interface type. Using a struct here avoids a heap allocation for the context object itself on every damage calculation (a hot path), since `DamagePipeline` constructs a fresh `DamageContext` per call. Modifiers in the chain only read `ctx`, never write back to it — if a future modifier needs to write a value the rest of the chain should see, change the relevant `IDamageModifier.Modify` signature to take `ref DamageContext ctx` rather than reintroducing a class here.

**Context/deps structs** (`DamageContext`, `AbilityContext`, `AbilityTargetDeps`) validate required references in the constructor (`ArgumentNullException`) — same fail-fast rule as service classes. **Event structs** do not; see `error-handling.mdc`.

```csharp
public readonly struct DamageContext
{
    public ICombatEntity Source { get; }
    public ICombatEntity Target { get; }
    public DamageType DamageType { get; }
    public bool IsCrit { get; }

    public DamageContext(ICombatEntity source, ICombatEntity target, DamageType damageType, bool isCrit) { ... }
}
```

`AbilityContext` is a `readonly struct`, initialized through its constructor. Do not add fields to it after construction. It holds `Target` (`AbilityTargetDeps` bundle) so target Entity/EventBus/BuffApplier stay cohesive — rejects `!target.IsValid` with `ArgumentException` (guards `default(AbilityTargetDeps)`). It holds `ICooldownQuery` (not `CooldownManager`) for read-only cooldown checks. It holds `RandomProvider` (`IRandomProvider`) for crit rolls — never use `UnityEngine.Random` in abilities. It also holds `AbilityIndex` and `Config` — per-entity execution dependencies injected by `AbilitySystem`, not stored on factory-created `IAbility` flyweights. Cooldown gating for `TryExecute` is owned by `AbilitySystem` (`IsOnCooldown` → `OnCooldown`); `IAbility.CanExecute` is a separate non-cooldown gate (`false` → `Fail(Blocked)`).

**All `IAbility` / `AbilityBase` methods take `in AbilityContext ctx`** to avoid defensive struct copies on a non-hot but multi-field struct.

`AbilityTargetDeps` is a `readonly struct` bundling the target's execution dependencies: `Entity` (`ICombatEntity`), `EventBus` (target's local bus), and `BuffApplier` (`IBuffApplier`). Constructor fail-fasts per field; `IsValid` is the single composite invariant (used by `AbilityContext`). `IAbilityTargetProvider.ToAbilityTarget()` on `Player`/`Enemy` builds it. `AbilitySystem.TryExecute` takes `AbilityTargetDeps` instead of separate target/bus/applier parameters. Self-target abilities pass the caster's own `ToAbilityTarget()`.

```csharp
public readonly struct AbilityContext
{
    public readonly ICombatEntity Caster;
    public readonly AbilityTargetDeps Target;
    public readonly int AbilityIndex;
    public readonly AbilityConfig Config;
    public readonly DamagePipeline DamagePipeline;
    public readonly ICooldownQuery CooldownQuery;
    public readonly IRandomProvider RandomProvider;

    public ICombatEntity TargetEntity => Target.Entity;
    public IEventBus TargetEventBus => Target.EventBus;
    public IBuffApplier TargetBuffApplier => Target.BuffApplier;

    public AbilityContext(
        ICombatEntity caster,
        AbilityTargetDeps target,
        int abilityIndex,
        AbilityConfig config,
        DamagePipeline damagePipeline,
        ICooldownQuery cooldownQuery,
        IRandomProvider randomProvider) { ... }
}

// Wrong — do not expose mutable CooldownManager to abilities
public readonly struct AbilityContext
{
    public readonly CooldownManager CooldownManager;
}
```

```csharp
[Serializable]
public struct AbilitySlot
{
    public AbilityConfig Config;
    public AbilityType AbilityType;
}
```

```csharp
public interface IAbilityFactory
{
    IAbility Create(AbilityType abilityType);
    Type GetExpectedConfigType(AbilityType abilityType);
}

public sealed class AbilityFactory : IAbilityFactory
{
    // Single dictionary of Registration { Creator, ExpectedConfigType }; Register in ctor / Demo (no overwrite).
    public IAbility Create(AbilityType abilityType) { ... }
    public Type GetExpectedConfigType(AbilityType abilityType) { ... }
    public void Register(AbilityType abilityType, Func<IAbility> creator, Type expectedConfigType) { ... } // duplicate → InvalidOperationException
}
```

```csharp
public readonly struct AbilityTargetDeps
{
    public readonly ICombatEntity Entity;
    public readonly IEventBus EventBus;
    public readonly IBuffApplier BuffApplier;

    public bool IsValid => Entity != null && EventBus != null && BuffApplier != null;

    public AbilityTargetDeps(ICombatEntity entity, IEventBus eventBus, IBuffApplier buffApplier) { ... }
}
```

Do not introduce `record` types for context or event types in this project — stick to the `class`/`readonly struct` patterns above.

## StatModifier

`StatModifier` is a pure C# class (not struct — it is passed by reference across collections). All fields are `readonly` and initialized via constructor. There are no setters.

**Buff-applied modifiers:** When an `IBuffEffect` adds a `StatModifier` (e.g. `SlowEffect`), `Source` **must be the `BuffInstance`**, not `BuffConfig`. `OnRemove` calls `RemoveModifiersFromSource(instance)`. Using `BuffConfig` as source breaks Independent stacking — removing one instance would remove all modifiers from that config.

**Stack mode:** one modifier per instance; `Value = configBase × BuffInstance.StackCount`; on stack change, **remove + re-add** a new `StatModifier` (no in-place update — `StatModifier` is immutable).
**Refresh mode:** do not add a new modifier; reset duration only.

```csharp
public sealed class StatModifier
{
    public StatType StatType { get; }
    public StatModifierType ModifierType { get; }
    public float Value { get; }
    public object Source { get; }

    public StatModifier(StatType statType, StatModifierType modifierType, float value, object source) { ... }
}
```

**Portfolio note:** `Source` is `object` for flexibility at demo scale. Buff-applied modifiers **must** use `BuffInstance` as source (see above). A marker interface (e.g. `IModifierSource`) would tighten removal semantics in production.

## Serialization Attributes

`[SerializeField]`, `[SerializeReference]`, and `[CreateAssetMenu]` belong on `MonoBehaviour` and
`ScriptableObject` subclasses. Do **not** add them to ordinary pure C# gameplay services
(`StatCollection`, `Damageable`, `CooldownManager`, …).

**Allowed exceptions** (Unity nesting requirements):
- `[Serializable]` on `AbilitySlot` (and similar slot/bundle structs embedded in SO configs)
- `[Serializable]` / `[SerializeReference]` on future `IBuffEffect` fields hosted by `BuffConfig` (when Buff lands)

```csharp
// Wrong — pure gameplay service
public class StatCollection
{
    [SerializeField] private float _baseAttack;
}

// Correct — SO owns serialized data; AbilitySlot stores Config + AbilityType (factory resolves IAbility)
public class PlayerConfig : ScriptableObject
{
    [SerializeField] private StatBaseEntry[] _statBases;
    [SerializeField] private List<AbilitySlot> _abilitySlots;
}
```

## ScriptableObjects

Every **concrete, designer-creatable** `ScriptableObject` subclass must have a `[CreateAssetMenu]` attribute. Do not generate a creatable ScriptableObject without it.

**Exception:** abstract bases (e.g. `AbilityConfig`) must **not** have `[CreateAssetMenu]` — only concrete subclasses (e.g. `DamageAbilityConfig`, `BuffConfig`, Demo `PlayerConfig` / `EnemyConfig`).

```csharp
// Abstract base — no CreateAssetMenu
public abstract class AbilityConfig : ScriptableObject
{
    [SerializeField] private float _cooldownDuration;
    [SerializeField] private BuffConfig _onHitBuff;

    public float CooldownDuration => _cooldownDuration;
    public BuffConfig OnHitBuff => _onHitBuff;
}

[CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Ability/Config/DamageAbilityConfig", fileName = "DamageAbilityConfig")]
public class DamageAbilityConfig : AbilityConfig { ... }

[CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Ability/Config/BuffConfig", fileName = "BuffConfig")]
public class BuffConfig : ScriptableObject { ... }

// Demo entity configs live under Demo/ — not Ability/Config/
[CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Demo/Config/PlayerConfig", fileName = "PlayerConfig")]
public class PlayerConfig : ScriptableObject
{
    [SerializeField] private StatBaseEntry[] _statBases;
    [SerializeField] private List<AbilitySlot> _abilitySlots;

    public IReadOnlyList<AbilitySlot> AbilitySlots => _abilitySlots;
    public void ApplyBaseStats(StatCollection stats) { ... }  // SetBaseStat per entry
}

[CreateAssetMenu(menuName = "Demo/Config/EnemyConfig", fileName = "EnemyConfig")]
public class EnemyConfig : ScriptableObject
{
    [SerializeField] private StatBaseEntry[] _statBases;
    public void ApplyBaseStats(StatCollection stats) { ... }
}
```

ScriptableObjects in this project are configuration assets only (`AbilityConfig`, `BuffConfig`, `PlayerConfig`, `EnemyConfig`). Do not store mutable runtime state inside a ScriptableObject field — a ScriptableObject asset is shared across all instances that reference it, so writing runtime state to it (e.g. current cooldown remaining, current buff stacks) corrupts state for every entity sharing that asset. Runtime state belongs in pure C# classes owned per-entity (`CooldownManager`, `BuffSystem`, `BuffInstance`).

Do not use a ScriptableObject as a service locator, event channel, or singleton accessor in this project. Factory-created `IAbility` flyweights must not cache or mutate per-entity runtime state (no `CooldownManager` in the constructor). Per-entity execution dependencies (`ICooldownQuery`, slot `Config`, `AbilityIndex`, `Random`) are passed through `AbilityContext` by `AbilitySystem`. Cooldown *state* lives in `CooldownManager`, not on the `IAbility` instance.

`[SerializeReference] IBuffEffect` on `BuffConfig` (when Buff lands) follows the same rule: shared flyweight implementations must not hold per-entity runtime state. Stacks, duration, and instance-specific data live on `BuffInstance` only.

`AbilityConfig.OnHitBuff` is an optional `BuffConfig` applied to the ability **Target**
(instigator = caster) after a **successful living-target hit path** — including when pipeline
damage is **0**. It is **not** applied when `DamageAbility` rejects a **dead** target
(`CanExecute` false / `Execute` `Fail(Blocked)` → no CD, no buff). Applied **after**
`DamagePipeline.Execute`, so it does not affect this hit's damage (post-hit DoT/debuff
semantics). Hit-type abilities call **`ApplyOnHitBuff(in ctx)`** via
`ctx.TargetBuffApplier.Apply(config, ctx.Caster)`; `AbilitySystem` must not apply it.
Self-buff skills pass the caster as target via `ToAbilityTarget()`.

## StatCollection Formula

`Stat.GetRawValue()` / `StatCollection.GetValue(StatType)` compute: `(base + Σ Additive) × (1 + Σ Percent)`. Additive modifiers accumulate first; Percent modifiers **sum into one multiplier** (not chained as `(1+p1)×(1+p2)`). Example: base=100, +50 Additive, +10% and +20% → `(100+50) × 1.3 = 195`. This formula is an invariant — do not reorder Additive/Percent phases or switch to product-of-percents.

`StatCollection.GetValue` then applies per-stat clamps: `MaxHealth` / `MoveSpeed` ≥ 0; `CritChance` ∈ [0, 1]; `AttackPower` / `Defense` / `CritDamage` stay unclamped (debuffs may go negative).

**MaxHealth mutations and clamp:** Prefer mutating effective MaxHealth via `AddModifier` / `RemoveModifier` / `RemoveModifiersFromSource` (or `SetBaseStat` when intentionally changing base). `StatCollection` publishes `StatChangedEvent` on the local `IEventBus` when the **clamped** resolved value changes. `Damageable` subscribes and, when `StatType == MaxHealth`, calls `ClampCurrentHealthToMax()`. Do not call clamp only from `BuffSystem` — any path that changes MaxHealth through Stats must publish so the subscription fires.

## Stat Caching

`Stat.GetRawValue()` uses a **dirty-flag cache** invalidated on `SetBaseValue` / `AddModifier` / `RemoveModifier` / `RemoveModifiersFromSource`. Do not recompute the full modifier list on every read in hot paths. This is separate from `Damageable.MaxHealth`: `Damageable` must not cache MaxHealth as its own field — it always reads `_stats.GetValue(StatType.MaxHealth)`, which may return a value backed by `Stat`'s cache then clamped by `StatCollection`.

## MaxHealth Source of Truth

`StatCollection` is the single source of truth for `MaxHealth` (modifiable by buffs via `StatModifier`). `Damageable` (`Gameplay/Combat/`) holds `CurrentHealth` as a field, but exposes `MaxHealth` as a read-only property that proxies `StatCollection.GetValue(StatType.MaxHealth)` on every access — it is never cached as a field on `Damageable`. Construct local `EventBus` + `StatCollection(eventBus)`, call `SetBaseStat` for required stats (including `MaxHealth`), then construct `Damageable(owner, stats, eventBus)` on the same bus (entity init order: `ARCHITECTURE_Detailed.md`; MaxHealth / event rules: `architecture.mdc`).

```csharp
// Gameplay/Stats/StatCollection.cs
public sealed class StatCollection : IReadOnlyStatCollection
{
    public StatCollection(IEventBus eventBus) { ... }

    public void SetBaseStat(StatType statType, float baseValue) { ... }
    public float GetValue(StatType type) { ... }
    public bool TryGetValue(StatType type, out float value) { ... }
    public void AddModifier(StatModifier modifier) { ... }   // may publish StatChangedEvent
    public bool RemoveModifier(StatModifier modifier) { ... }
    public void RemoveModifiersFromSource(object source) { ... }
}

// Gameplay/Combat/Damageable.cs — subscribes to StatChangedEvent in ctor (MaxHealth → ClampCurrentHealthToMax)
public sealed class Damageable
{
    public Damageable(ICombatEntity owner, IReadOnlyStatCollection stats, IEventBus eventBus) { ... }

    public void ClampCurrentHealthToMax() { ... }  // Min(CurrentHealth, MaxHealth); HealthChangedEvent if changed
    // ...
}
```

UI may read MaxHealth from `StatCollection` or `Damageable.MaxHealth` (always agree). Any MaxHealth change via Stats API that changes the resolved value → `StatChangedEvent` → `ClampCurrentHealthToMax()`.

`TakeDamage()` throws `ArgumentOutOfRangeException` when `amount < 0`, subtracts damage, clamps `CurrentHealth` to `>= 0`, then publishes `HealthChangedEvent`; it does not publish `DamageEvent` (see `architecture.mdc`). `Heal()` throws on `amount < 0`, clamps to live `MaxHealth`, publishes `HealthChangedEvent` and `HealEvent`.
